<dl id="n54107j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54107j">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54107j"> 107(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Mussab (bestdressed) <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54107j"><li>FW 318.25f </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n54107j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n54107j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54107j">MS BL 47479-173</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:267 <a name="mad6" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n54107j">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When the new converts returned to Yathrib, Mohammed sent with them a young man named <mark>Musab</mark>, to teach them the doctrines of the Kor&#257;n, and to lead them in their prayers. Musab, at one time known as the <mark>best-dressed</mark> man in Meccah, was a great grandson of Hashim, but his mother and her tribe were so bitterly opposed to the Prophet that his conversion to Isl&#257;m was, at first, kept secret. When it became known, Musab was disowned by his mother and her family, and was forced to fly, with the first emigrants, to Abyssinia <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 73</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
